lly, the attainment of elder status and death. He relates men's struggles both to fulfill their own aspirations and to meet society's expectations. He also considers men who behave badly, mistreat their wives and children, or resort to crime and violence. All of these men face similar challenges as they navigate the complex geometry of money and intimacy. Unraveling these connections, Smith argues, provides us with a deeper understanding of both masculinity and society in Nigeria.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aIgbo (African people)xSocial life and customs. 0aMasculinityxEconomic aspectszNigeria. 0aMenzNigeriaxSocial conditions. 0aMen--Nigeria--Social conditions. 0aMoneyxSocial aspectszNigeria. 4aNigeria. 4aconspicuous redistribution. 4aeconomics. 4aintimacy. 4amanhood. 4amasculinity. 4amen. 4amoney. 4asocial relations. 4asociliaty. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226491790423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226491790.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles